                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d48">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00 R 29/648: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Commissioner at Berlin</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dresel</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-04-21T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 21, 1921—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>718. Department’s telegram no. 717, April 21. You may tell Simons informally and
                    confidentially that although this Government could not act as umpire in
                    settlement of reparations problem, it would be willing with concurrence of
                    Allied Governments to take part in the negotiations if Germany seeks to resume
                    them on a sound basis.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
